\begin_layout Chapter
Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section defines various types of polynomials.
 For example orthogonal polynomials are going to be important further on.
 They are defined by a property that the inner product of any two distinct orthogonal polynomials within a sequence is zero.
 The inner product employed throughout this work is defined via integration over a specified interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 with respect to a continuous weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in C(I)$
\end_inset

.
 A key characteristic of orthogonal polynomials,
 and by extension their normalized counterparts (orthonormal polynomials),
 is that they satisfy a three-term recurrence relation.
 The coefficients of this recurrence relation can be arranged into a symmetric tridiagonal matrix,
 known as the Jacobi matrix.
 The eigenpairs of this Jacobi matrix provide a direct method for determining the roots of the orthogonal polynomials.
 The chapter concludes with a discussion on Gaussian quadrature rules,
 which utilize the roots of orthogonal polynomials as nodes and derived values as weights for numerical integration.
 The eigenvalue (spectral) decomposition of the aforementioned Jacobi matrix yields via Golub-Welsch algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GolubWelsch1969"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 these quadrature nodes and weights.
 For Legendre polynomials we also show how to extend them over a finite interval with the use of a simple affine change of variables.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Furthermore,
 the specific case leading to Legendre polynomials is examined,
 corresponding to integration over an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with a unity weight function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


