\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
We can consider rolls of dice as an example of probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In a roll of a die there are six possible outcomes and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5,6\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For a sequence of M rolls,
 the sample space is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5,6\right\} ^{M}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

,
 these subsets are known as events.
 Each event corresponds to a set of outcomes in the experiment.
 Let's say we want to know the probability of rolling an even number and so the set 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} $
\end_inset

 is included as an event in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Lastly we have the probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset

,
 which assigns a probability to every measurable set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Probability will be a number between 0 and 1,
 where 0 means the even will never occur and one means the event will always occur.
 Higher probability means the event is more likely to occur in an experiment.
 For a fair dice roll the probability of rolling an even number would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left(\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} \right)=1/2$
\end_inset

.
