\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section addresses the Karhunen-Loève (KL) expansion,
 specifically focusing on its application to Isotropic Gaussian Random Fields for which we will consider the expected value will be equal to 0,
 i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]=0$
\end_inset

 .
 Subsequently,
 a numerical approximation of the KL expansion is pursued using the Galerkin method.
 The implementation of this method involves the computation of integrals over the specified multi-dimensional domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Gaussian quadrature techniques are employed for the efficient numerical evaluation of these integrals.
 The determination of the eigenfunctions and eigenvalues required for the KL expansion inherently corresponds to solving an integral eigenvalue problem,
 which is conceptually equivalent to the spectral decomposition of the covariance operator associated with the random field.
 The Galerkin procedure provides a means to discretize this problem,
 leading to a matrix eigenvalue problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
